"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=5DE7BC77-6402-4B80-A5E9-9E8AC3644D45&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Frepublican-gop-virginia-2023-midterms-state-house-senate-assembly-youngkin-trump-2024-presidential-election-ded7e02a&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> Journal Editorial Report: The Department of Justice accelerates its legal offensive. Images: Zuma Press/AFP/Getty Images Composite: Mark Kelly <span class="imageCredit">The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition</span></p></div></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 11 Aug 2023 22:07:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/republican-gop-virginia-2023-midterms-state-house-senate-assembly-youngkin-trump-2024-presidential-election-ded7e02a</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/republican-gop-virginia-2023-midterms-state-house-senate-assembly-youngkin-trump-2024-presidential-election-ded7e02a<author><![CDATA[Kate Bachelder Odell]]></author><category> virginia</category><category> 2023 election</category><category> state senate</category><category> state house</category><category> races</category><category> campaign</category><category> 2024 presidential campaign</category><category> midterms</category><category> gop primary</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>Regional Politics</category><category>选举</category><category>国家/总统选举</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>regional politics</category><category>选举</category><category>national</category><category>总统选举</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[New York’s Map Drama Could Make Hakeem Jeffries House Speaker]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Democrats in Albany try everything they can to replace fair districts with gerrymandered ones. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11221797970291203701404590130683952263228"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11221797970291203701404590130683952263228"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name">John J. Faso</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 11, 2023 6:07 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/albanys-map-drama-could-make-hakeem-jeffries-house-speaker-harkenrider-court-of-appeals-50544b78"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833726?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> The New York state Capitol building in Albany, NY, June 20.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Hans Pennink/Associated Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> A radical effort by state and national Democrats to undermine New York&#39;s democracy is flying under the radar. While many on the political left rail against real and imagined “threats to democracy,” House Minority Leader Hakeem Jeffries is attempting to get New York courts to order a redraft of the state&#39;s congressional districts. This would give Democrats an advantage in the 2024 elections and potentially make Mr. Jeffries speaker.</p><p> In 2014, New York voters passed a constitutional amendment strictly limiting both partisan gerrymandering and the Legislature&#39;s power over redistricting. Mr. Jeffries and state Democrats were stung last year when the Court of Appeals, the state&#39;s highest court, rejected a congressional redistricting scheme enacted by the Legislature. In <em>Harkenrider v. Hochul</em> the court found the plan unconstitutional on two grounds. First, it was a partisan gerrymander that was illegally crafted to aid Democrats and disadvantage Republicans. Second, the plan was enacted contrary to the express procedure prescribed by the amendment.</p><p> The amendment limited the Legislature&#39;s power through the creation of an Independent Redistricting Commission, a 10-member body charged with drafting legislative and congressional districts. The commission was to submit a plan to the Legislature, which could accept or reject but not amend it. If lawmakers rejected the initial proposal, the commission could submit a second plan. Only after the Legislature rejected that plan could lawmakers enact their own plan.</p><p> The Legislature rejected the commission&#39;s first map in January 2022. The commission then deadlocked and couldn&#39;t agree on a second plan. On Feb. 3, 2022, the Legislature enacted its own plan, which an analyst with the left-leaning Brennan Center called a “master class in gerrymandering.” Under maps drawn after the 2010 Census, Republicans held eight of New York&#39;s 27 House seats. The new census gave New York 26 seats, and the Legislature&#39;s new map packed most Republican voters into a mere four districts around the state.</p><p> Republicans sued, challenging the plan on the day it was enacted. Under court supervision, a nonpartisan expert crafted a redistricting plan that followed the requirements of the state constitution and protected voting rights of minorities. Significantly, the plan also created nine competitive congressional districts, more than any other state. Under this plan, New York Republicans won 11 seats in 2022, arguably shifting control of the US House.</p><p> The Court of Appeals will soon hear a new case brought by Mr. Jeffries and allied Democrats who argue that <em>Harkenrider</em> applied only to the 2022 election cycle and that new lines should be crafted for the balance of the decade. While Democrats lost their case in the trial court in September, an appellate court in Albany, in a 3-2 decision, recently ruled that the Independent Redistricting Commission and the Legislature should get another chance to redraw the districts. Democrats argue that this will promote greater transparency and provide for meaningful public participation in the process.</p><p> These arguments are specious. Under the state constitution, mid-decade redistricting is never permitted unless a violation of law is found. That violation was remedied when the Court of Appeals ordered a new map last year. Another round of congressional districts would confuse the public and undermine political competition. Mr. Jeffries and Democrats in Washington and Albany want a do-over because they think are pursuing power, not good government.</p><p> Indeed, Democrats attempted to subvert the 2014 amendment as soon as they gained legislative supermajorities in 2018. Their sole aim was to return unfettered power to the Legislature to craft the congressional map. They didn&#39;t even want to fund the redistricting commission as required by law. In 2021 the Albany-based Government Justice Center had to sue to get them to do it. Democrats then proposed a constitutional amendment that eliminated any practical role for Republicans on the commission and made it easier for the Legislature to take over the job of redistricting. Voters defeated that amendment. Undaunted, Democrats passed a statute mirroring the failed amendment, which the Court of Appeals found unconstitutional in <em>Harkenrider</em> .</p><p> Angry at the court, state Senate Democrats blocked the nomination of Justice Hector LaSalle</p> to be its chief judge with phony allegations about his record. Their real intention was to overturn last year&#39;s redistricting decision and send an unmistakable message that progressives are in charge. Ruling Democrats say their next objective is to abolish the merit-based selection process for Court of Appeals judges, thereby undermining judicial independence.<p></p><p> But first the Court of Appeals will hear the challenge to <em>Harkenrider</em> . The judges face a stark choice: either they capitulate to Mr. Jeffries, who dreams of redistricting his way to the speaker&#39;s chair, or they defend democracy by upholding their independence and the integrity of New York&#39;s electoral system.</p><p> <em>Mr. Faso, a Republican, served as US representative from New York&#39;s 19th District (2017-19) and Republican leader in the New York Assembly (1998-2002). He was the GOP nominee for governor in 2006.</em> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
